items.description: In this section, we learn how to solve optimization problems. These are problems in which we are looking for the best way to do something. This might be the cheapest way to make a container, or the number of items to be produced and sold to maximize profits, or simply the maximum area to be enclosed by a fixed amount of fencing. We've all seen optimization problems in high school algebra courses. Those problems always involved finding the maximum or minimum value of a quadratic function, and the solution always required finding the vertex of the parabola. Here, we are able to find the maximum or minimum value of any differentiable function.

In this section we look at both indefinite integrals and definite integrals. An indefinite integral is another name for a general antiderivative. Here, we'll get more practice finding antiderivatives and using them to evaluate definite integrals. We also learn a new way to view the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus Part 2: The Net Change Theorem says that the definite integral from a to b of a rate of change function is just the net change of the function over the time interval from t= a to t=b. This is useful for applications.

Here is where we put it all together to sketch accurate graphs without simply plotting random points. This is a very important Calculus 1 topic, and one of the main reasons for not allowing graphing calculators on exams. If, on this assignment, you want to use a graphing utility to check your graph, that's ok. But you won't be allowed to do that on a quiz or exam, so don't become too dependent on your calculator!

items.summary: 3.6 Derivatives of Logarithmic Functions  Log Dif [MATH-192-2926]
items.description:
Now that we've used Implicit Differentiation to get formulas for differentiating logarithmic functions, we've added some tools to our toolbox. We have several new formulas for differentiating logarithmic functions, but We also get a great new tool, called Logarithmic Differentiation, which allows us to differentiate complicated functions involving products, quotients, and powers. Taking the logarithm of both sides of a complicated equation turns products into sums, quotients into differences, and simplifies expressions with variables in the base as well as in the exponent.

There are at least four videos that you should watch to prepare for this assignment. Three of them [on on this page] (https://4cd.instructure.com/courses/57115/pages/videos-differentiation-of-logarithmic-functions). The other one is right before this assignment. (Click on Previous to go back to it.)
In this section, we use the Product Rule and the Quotient Rule to find the derivatives of products and quotients of differentiable functions.

The Chain Rule allows us to differentiate a composite function, f(g(x)). It also allows us to finally differentiate an exponential function with base b. Make sure that you know how both of these things work!

In this section, we are doing more applications of the derivative. In these problems, we are applying the Chain Rule to real-life situations where multiple quantities are changing with respect to time. Those changing quantities are related by an equation, and when you differentiate both sides of that equation with respect to time, you get a new equation that relates the derivatives.
Welcome to the last assignment of the semester! In this assignment, you'll compute the area between the graphs of two continuous functions.

In this section, we start treating the derivative of a function as a function in its own right. For example, instead of looking for the derivative of f(x) = x^2 at a particular number x = a, we often want to have a formula that will give us the derivative of f(x) = x^2 at ANY point. If we use the definition of the derivative of f at a number a, but replace a with the variable x, we get the function f'(x) = 2x. That means that we can use this new function to find the derivative of f at any point that we might be interested in. In this assignment, we get lots of practice with limits again.

In this section, we use our new differentiation rules for trigonometric functions. The derivative of sin x is cos x, and the derivative of cos x is -sin x. The other four trig derivatives are easy to derive from these two (using the quotient rule) if you aren't good at memorizing (Dr. G. is terrible at memorizing). Also in this section, we learn that the limit as x--> 0 of (sin x / x) is 1 and that the limit as x-->0 of (cos x -1)/x is 0. These limits come in handy on some problems in the homework, and we will see them again later in the semester.

We now define something new, called the definite integral, which is a generalization of the notion of area under a curve or distance traveled. The definite integral of a continuous function on the interval [a,b] is defined as the limit of a sequence of finite sums. If f is continuous and happens to be positive on the interval [a,b], then the definite integral of f from a to b is just the area under the curve along that interval (or the distance traveled). Also, we can express any area under a positive function (or distance traveled) as a definite integral. But definite integrals aren't just used for areas or distances; we can also compute the definite integral of any continuous function, not simply a positive one.

Here is where we can start differentiating polynomials and exponential functions without having to use the limit definition of the derivative. You'll need to start memorizing differentiation formulas. The best way to do that is by doing a lot of problems!

Remember: When you use a calculator to compute something irrational like ln(2), your calculator is giving you an approximation. How does it compute that approximation? It uses a polynomial. In this section, we use a first degree polynomial (called the linearization or the tangent line) to approximate the value of a function near a particular point.

In this section, we learn about two important theorems. The first one is called Rolle's Theorem, and it tells us that if there are two points on a differentiable curve where the y-coordinates are the same, then there is a horizontal tangent line at some point in between. Rolle's Theorem can be used in conjunction with the Intermediate value Theorem from Chapter 2 to show that an equation has exactly one root. It is also used to prove the Mean Value Theorem, which basically says that there is a tangent line that is parallel to the secant line connecting two points on a differentiable curve.

Now we get to see the connection between differentiation and integration. The Fundamental Theorem of Calculus has two parts. The first part tells us explicitly what the connection is, and the second part tells us how to use an antiderivative to evaluate a definite integral.
In this section, we use all the tools that we've accumulated to solve problems in science and social science involving rates of change. This is what calculus is all about!

In this section, we learn how to integrate certain products of functions, namely a composite times the differential of its "inside" function: f(g(x))g'(x)dx . This is the "opposite" of the Chain Rule for differentiation.

In this section, we learn how to find the area under a curve by taking the limit of a finite sum (as the number of terms in that sum goes to infinity) of areas of rectangles. We'll use sigma notation for the finite sums so that our sums are more compact-looking.
Here is where we apply what we've learned about absolute maxima and absolute minima to real-world situations.

In this section, we look at applications (word problems) in which the rate of change of a quantity at a particular time is proportional to the size of the quantity at that time. In other words, dy/dt = ky, where k is some constant. If k is positive, the quantity is increasing (growth), and if k is negative, the quantity is decreasing (decay). It turns out that the only functions that have this property are exponential functions, so y has to have the form y = Ce^(kt), where C is the initial quantity (C = y(0)). This assignment looks shorter than most, but because it consists of applications (word problems), you will need to allow ample time to finish.

In this section, we begin exploring the operation of going from a derivative to the original function. Remember that F(x) is an antiderivative of f if F'(x) = f(x), and that F(x) + C (where C is an arbitrary constant) is called the most general antiderivative of f. For example, F(x) = 3x^2 is an antiderivative of f(x) = x^3 for all real numbers, and F(x) = 3x^2 + C is the most general antiderivative of f(x) = x^3.

(The Account class)

Design a class named Account that contains:

■ A private int data field named id for the account (default 0).
